Use Case Layer (Domain)
Responsibilities — exactly one per class:

Execute exactly one business operation
Combine data from one or more repositories (never two data sources directly)
Apply business rules, validation, and transformations
Return Result<T> or Flow<Result<T>>
Hard rules:

✗  No Android framework imports (no Context, no Activity, no LifecycleOwner)
✗  No direct data source access (never import a DAO or Retrofit service)
✗  No UI-related types in return values
✗  Never combine unrelated business actions in one UseCase
✓  One public method: operator fun invoke() — makes the call site read as a function call
✓  Testable with plain JUnit, no mocking of Android framework
✓  Depends only on Repository interfaces, never implementations

UseCase template:

class [Verb][Noun]UseCase @Inject constructor(
    private val [noun]Repository: [Noun]Repository
) {
    suspend operator fun invoke(param: [ParamType]): Result<[ReturnType]> {
        // Validate inputs
        require(param.[field].isNotBlank()) { "[Field] must not be blank" }
        // Delegate to repository
        return [noun]Repository.[operation](param)
    }
}
// Streaming variant:
class Get[Noun]UseCase @Inject constructor(
    private val [noun]Repository: [Noun]Repository
) {
    operator fun invoke(): Flow<Result<List<[DomainModel]>>> =
        [noun]Repository.get[Noun]Stream()
}

UseCase naming rules:

✓  GetRecordingsUseCase       — retrieves data
✓  SaveRecordingUseCase       — persists data
✓  DeleteRecordingUseCase     — removes data
✓  AuthenticateUserUseCase    — business action
✓  ApplyVoiceEffectUseCase    — transformation
✗  RecordingUseCase           — too vague, action unclear
✗  HandleRecordingUseCase     — "handle" is meaningless
✗  RecordingManagerUseCase    — "manager" violates SRP naming

Repository Layer (Domain Interface + Data Implementation)
Repository Interface lives in domain. Repository Implementation lives in data.

Interface responsibilities:

Define the contract for data operations
Return domain models, never DTOs or entities
Use Flow<Result<T>> for streaming, suspend fun returning Result<T> for one-shots
Implementation responsibilities:

Decide which data source to call (remote, local, cache)
Implement cache-first or network-first strategy explicitly
Map DTOs and Entities to Domain Models via Mapper classes
Wrap all data source errors into Result.failure
Hard rules:

✗  Interface never imports Room, Retrofit, or any framework class
✗  Implementation never leaks DTO or Entity types past this layer
✗  Never combine two unrelated domains in one Repository
✗  ViewModel never knows which data source served the data
✗  Never duplicate a repository — if it exists, extend it; don't create a parallel one
✓  Repository interface is in :domain module or domain package
✓  Repository implementation is in :data module or data package
✓  Every implementation is registered in a Hilt module via @Binds
✓  Cache invalidation strategy is explicit — no silent stale data

Repository interface template:

interface [Domain]Repository {
    fun get[Domain]Stream(): Flow<Result<List<[DomainModel]>>>
    suspend fun get[Domain]ById(id: Long): Result<[DomainModel]>
    suspend fun save[Domain](model: [DomainModel]): Result<Long>
    suspend fun delete[Domain](id: Long): Result<Unit>
}

Repository implementation template:

class [Domain]RepositoryImpl @Inject constructor(
    private val remoteDataSource: [Domain]RemoteDataSource,
    private val localDataSource: [Domain]LocalDataSource,
    private val mapper: [Domain]Mapper
) : [Domain]Repository {
    override fun get[Domain]Stream(): Flow<Result<List<[DomainModel]>>> =
        localDataSource.getAll()
            .map { entities → Result.success(entities.map(mapper::toDomain)) }
            .catch { emit(Result.failure(it)) }
    override suspend fun save[Domain](model: [DomainModel]): Result<Long> =
        runCatching {
            localDataSource.insert(mapper.toEntity(model))
        }
}

Data Source Layer
Each data source talks to exactly one external system.

Types:

RemoteDataSource — Retrofit / GraphQL / WebSocket / Firebase
LocalDataSource — Room DAOs (never accessed directly from Repository)
CacheDataSource — in-memory LRU / disk cache / OkHttp cache
Hard rules:

✗  Never put two data source types in one class
✗  Never return DTOs from the Repository layer
✗  Never perform business logic in a DataSource
✓  RemoteDataSource returns DTOs (suspending Retrofit calls wrapped in runCatching)
✓  LocalDataSource returns Entities as Flow<List<Entity>> or suspend fun
✓  Every DataSource method has a single, focused responsibility

Remote DataSource template:

class [Domain]RemoteDataSource @Inject constructor(
    private val apiService: [Domain]ApiService
) {
    suspend fun fetch[Domain](): Result<[Domain]Dto> = runCatching {
        apiService.get[Domain]()
    }
}

Local DataSource template (wraps Room DAO):

class [Domain]LocalDataSource @Inject constructor(
    private val dao: [Domain]Dao
) {
    fun getAll(): Flow<List<[Domain]Entity>> = dao.getAll()
    suspend fun insert(entity: [Domain]Entity): Long = dao.insert(entity)
    suspend fun deleteById(id: Long) = dao.deleteById(id)
}

Mapper Layer
Every model boundary has a dedicated Mapper. No layer ever converts data itself.

Four model types — never reuse across layers:

Model Type	Layer	Contents
[Name]Dto	Data / Remote	API response fields, JSON-annotated
[Name]Entity	Data / Local	Room columns, no business logic
[Name] (Domain Model)	Domain	Business-meaningful fields, pure Kotlin
[Name]UiModel	Presentation	Display-ready fields (formatted strings, colors)
Mapper template:

class [Domain]Mapper @Inject constructor() {
    fun toDomain(dto: [Domain]Dto): [Domain] = [Domain](
        id = dto.id,
        title = dto.title.orEmpty(),
        createdAt = Instant.ofEpochMilli(dto.createdAtMs)
    )
    fun toDomain(entity: [Domain]Entity): [Domain] = [Domain](
        id = entity.id,
        title = entity.title,
        createdAt = Instant.ofEpochMilli(entity.createdAtMs)
    )
    fun toEntity(domain: [Domain]): [Domain]Entity = [Domain]Entity(
        id = domain.id,
        title = domain.title,
        createdAtMs = domain.createdAt.toEpochMilli()
    )
    fun toUiModel(domain: [Domain]): [Domain]UiModel = [Domain]UiModel(
        id = domain.id,
        displayTitle = domain.title.replaceFirstChar { it.uppercase() },
        formattedDate = domain.createdAt.toRelativeTimeString()
    )
}

