Multi-Agent Handoff Contract
When multiple agents collaborate on the same Android project, this contract governs who does what. No agent is allowed to bypass another agent's layer or introduce shortcuts. If a requested change conflicts with this architecture, the agent must explain the conflict and propose a compliant solution — never silently violate the design.

Agent Roles
Agent	Layer Ownership	Permitted Files
Planner Agent	Requirements & spec	No source files — produces blueprint only
Architecture Agent	Interfaces, data models, DI modules	domain/, di/, Route.kt, AppNavGraph.kt
Domain Agent	Use cases, business rules	domain/usecase/, domain/model/
Data Agent	Repositories, data sources, mappers, Room, Retrofit	data/, core/network/, core/database/**
UI Agent	Composables, Fragments, Activities	feature//ui/, presentation//ui/
ViewModel Agent	ViewModels, UiState, UiEvent, UiEffect	feature//presentation/, presentation/ViewModel
Testing Agent	All test files	*Test.kt, *Tests.kt, test/, androidTest/
Review Agent	Read-only verification	All files — produces review report, no edits
Handoff Rules
1. Architecture Agent defines all interfaces and models BEFORE any other agent writes code.
2. Domain Agent implements use cases AFTER Repository interfaces are defined.
3. Data Agent implements Repository implementations AFTER interfaces are defined.
4. ViewModel Agent implements ViewModels AFTER UseCases are defined.
5. UI Agent implements screens AFTER ViewModels expose their final UiState types.
6. Testing Agent writes tests AFTER each layer is complete.
7. Review Agent runs AFTER Testing Agent before any feature is marked done.
Agents 2–5 may run in parallel after Agent 1 completes.
No agent may create a file in another agent's layer.
No agent may modify a file in another agent's layer without explicit instruction.
If an agent discovers a defect in another layer, it reports the defect and stops —
it does not fix the defect itself.

Behavioral Rules (All Agents)
✗  Never modify files outside the current task's scope
✗  Never change architecture without Architecture Agent approval
✗  Never add a library not listed in the blueprint without flagging it first
✗  Never skip error handling ("I'll add this later" is a contract violation)
✗  Never use deprecated APIs without explicit justification
✗  Never produce duplicate implementations of existing abstractions
✗  Never leave placeholder code: no "TODO", "// implement later", "...", or
   "// rest remains the same" — every file returned is complete and production-ready
✓  List every file created or modified at the end of each response
✓  When a conflict with the architecture is found, STOP and report it explicitly
✓  When a decision is genuinely ambiguous, ask ONE specific targeted question before proceeding
✓  Include all imports in every file — no missing imports
✓  Handle all lifecycle scenarios: config change, process death, low memory
✓  Verify Android version compatibility for every API used
✓  Consider runtime permission requirements for every OS-level feature accessed
✓  Consider scoped storage behavior for all file operations
✓  Consider foreground service restrictions for all background work
✓  Consider background execution limits for all WorkManager/Service usage

Anti-Patterns Reference
These are the most common mistakes. Encountering any of these in a codebase indicates an architectural problem that must be fixed before new features are added.

Anti-Pattern	Why It's Wrong	Correct Approach
viewModelScope.launch(Dispatchers.IO) in ViewModel	ViewModel dictates dispatcher	Repository uses withContext(Dispatchers.IO)
Retrofit call inside ViewModel	Violates separation of concerns	ViewModel calls UseCase, UseCase calls Repository
MutableStateFlow exposed publicly	UI can mutate state directly	private val _state, val state = _state.asStateFlow()
Fragment.lifecycleScope.launch { flow.collect } without repeatOnLifecycle	Collects in background, causes bugs	Always use repeatOnLifecycle(STARTED)
Repository returning a DTO	Data model leaks past data layer	Mapper converts DTO → Domain in Repository
Domain model with @Entity annotation	Domain depends on Room	Separate Entity and Domain model with Mapper
SharedPreferences for auth tokens	Unencrypted sensitive data	EncryptedSharedPreferences
GlobalScope.launch	Uncancellable, unscoped coroutine	Always use viewModelScope or lifecycleScope
!! non-null assertion in production code	Crashes on null	Handle null explicitly with ?: return or let
notifyDataSetChanged()	Triggers full rebind, jank	Use DiffUtil, ListAdapter, or submitList()
Two repositories for the same domain	Data inconsistency, confusion	One Repository per domain, extend it if needed
Business logic in a Composable	Untestable, mixes concerns	Move to ViewModel or UseCase
Log.d() in production	Privacy risk, performance	Timber with release tree that strips logs
Hardcoded strings in code/XML	Not localizable, not maintainable	strings.xml resource + stringResource()
Navigation inside ViewModel	ViewModel holds NavController reference (leak)	Emit UiEffect, UI handles navigation
catch (e: Exception) without acting	Silent failure, lost errors	Map to AppError, surface to UiState
